@NODE "Requirements" "System Requirements"
@TOC "MAIN"
                              System Requirements

  This program should work on any Amiga with OS 2.0 or above.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Why" "Why?"
@TOC "MAIN"
                              Why Remind?


  Why not!
  Calender programs are plentiful for the Amiga, you can always find another
program sitting on a BBS/aminet which tells you what you are doing today. 
However I feel none of the programs I have tried actually are useful and 
easy to read.

  The good thing about remind is that it contains all the information in one
window, including what you need to do today, what you need to do within
several days, and what you have to do for the rest of the year. The user
interface has been remarked on by several people for its clarity.

  Its compact, completely configurable (well nearly), and it doesn't cost
that much. See @{"Introduction" LINK "Introduction"} for details.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Install" "Installation procedure"
@TOC "MAIN"
                           How to install Remind

To install Remind double click on the Remind-Install icon in the
archive directory. This will run the standard Amiga Installation
utility. If you do not have this installation utility it can be
obtained from nearly all public domain sites.
Follow the instructions given by the install icon.


If you are unable to obtain the Installation program, here is the manual
method...

How to install:

Drag the Remind icon into your WBStartup drawer, or where ever you
wish to start remind from.. This is the controlling program.

Now either create a new Remind drawer and drag Remind_GUI into
that new drawer, or drag Remind_GUI into a drawer where you would
like it located. (Note Remind_GUI should not be run by the user, Remind
will startup Remind_GUI)

Now, edit the file s:user-startup and append to the end of the file the
following:-

#Begin Remind
assign Remind: <Drawer location remind_GUI can be found>
#End Remind



for example, I have a drawer in work: called Remind, and Remind_GUI is in
this drawer, so my user-startup is

#Begin Remind
assign Remind: Work:Remind
#End Remind

Next, if your old version of Remind was before Version 1.6B then 
run the Convert program to update your data files.
Once convert has been run, the convert program can be deleted.

Now reboot, or double click on Remind icon....

Good luck...



The program will create two files.

ENVARC:remind.prefs   and
s:remind.data

  The s:remind.data file can be renamed if you so wish, see @{"prefs" LINK "Prefs"} section.

  When Remind starts up, how it behaves depends on the preference settings.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "No clock" "Systems with no built in clock"
@TOC "MAIN"
                         Systems with no built in clock

  If the 'freeze remind until clock set' flag is set in the @{"preferences" LINK "Prefs"}, a
window will appear indicating that remind is frozen.
  At this point the system clock should be set using the Time program in the
prefs drawer, or something similar. When the date has been set, click on the
'Ready' button to continue.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Startup" "The Startup window"
@TOC "MAIN"
                         The Startup Window

  If the value set for the 'Timer for startup' in the @{"preferences" LINK "Prefs"} is greater
than 0 then a small startup window will appear. This indicates that remind 
has been installed.
  When the startup window is active the program is doing no work, and the 
data file has not yet been loaded. This is to allow other programs in the
WBStartup draw to load, preventing disk thrashing.

  After the timer has expired then if

         The @{"preferences" LINK "Prefs"} has 'always' type set for startup
     or 
         The @{"preferences" LINK "Prefs"} has 'once' type set and the program has not been
         used today,

  then the main window will be opened,

  otherwise the startup window will disappear and the program will hide.

  Note, if the hotkey is pressed during the startup timer then the main 
window will open immediately irrespective of the startup type.

  Note, a value of 0 will disable to startup window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Today messages" "Today messages"
@TOC "MAIN"
                               Today messages

 If the preferences has the "Show messages for today" flag set then if this
is the first time the program has been run today for each of the messages
waiting for today a small window will appear displaying the message.

 If there are further messages today, clicking the "Ok" gadget will display
the next message, until all messages have been displayed.

 Any messages which have been missed (maybe you haven't started Remind
for a couple of days) will be displayed before Todays messages are shown.
Remind will inform you that the message has been "Missed"

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Control" "The Contolling process"
@TOC "MAIN"

			The controlling process

  Remind is split into two separate modules, a controlling process and
a main process.
  The controlling process deals with:
	- waiting for timers to expire
	- Opening/Closing main window
	- Processing a new day (if remind is left running over night)

  The controlling process should always be left running, it is event
triggered so it will not use any CPU resources unless required.

  The controlling process "Remind" should be moved into your WBStartup
drawer in you workbench partition. When this process starts up it
starts the Remind_GUI @{"Main window" LINK "Main window"} running depending on your preference
settings.

  In your s:user-startup script, you MUST define an assign to a Remind: 
drawer, so Remind can locate Remind_GUI, the installation script should
create this assign for you, if however it doesn't, then enter the following
lines into s:user-startup

;BEGIN Remind
assign Remind: <full path location of remind_gui>
;END Remind

for example, my setup is
;BEGIN Remind
assign Remind: work:my_programs/Remind
;END Remind

 When the hot key is pressed the controlling window will appear, you can
either:
	- Hit the GUI Show/Hide button to open or close the Remind_GUI
	- Hit Hide button to hide the controlling window
	- Hit Quit button to completely remove all of Remind from memory
	
 NOTE: hitting the hot key a second time is the same as hitting the GUI
show/hide button. So to open the main window hit the hot key twice, and to
close the main window, hit the hot key twice again.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Main window" "The Main Window"
@TOC "MAIN"
                               The Main window


 The main window is as following.

 _________________________________________________________________________
|O|_______________________________________________________________________|
|                                                                         |
|  ___________________________________________________________________ _  |
| |                                                                   | | |
| |      Expired messages                                             | | |
| |___________________________________________________________________|_| |
|  ___________________________________________________________________ _  |
| |                                                                   | | |
| |                                                                   | | |
| |      Todays messages                                              | | |
| |                                                                   | | |
| |___________________________________________________________________|_| |
|  ___________________________________________________________________ _  |
| |                                                                   | | |
| |      Messages within a set period                                 | | |
| |___________________________________________________________________|_| |
|  ___________________________________________________________________ _  |
| |                                                                   | | |
| |      Other future messages                                        | | |
| |___________________________________________________________________|_| |
|  ____________   ________________________                                |
| |@| Previous | |  O                     | 15 Percent                    |
| _____  ________  _______  _______  ______  ________  ______  _________  |
||     ||        ||       ||       ||      ||        ||      ||         | |
|| Add || Delete || Amend || Prefs || View || Normal || Quit || Finished| |
||_____||________||_______||_______||______||________||______||_________| |
|________________________________________________________________________V|


  The top list contains all messages which have passed their date,
  i.e. expired.

  The next list contains all messages for today.

  The third list contains all messages within the period set in the 
@{"preference" LINK "Prefs"} field 'Within period'. For example if today is 7th June and 
the within period is set to 7 then the third list contains all messages
for the 8th, 9th, 10th, 11th, 12th, 13th and 14th of June.

  The final list contains all other message in the future.

  The cycle gadget will change depending on which list you last clicked in
or you can change it yourself by clicking it. Next to this cycle gadget is
a percentage bar which indicates how much of the main window size is taken
up by the list indicated by the cycle gadget. For example if each percentage
was set to 25% then each of the windows would be the same size. The default
range is Previous 20%, Today 30%, Within 30%, Future 20%. This default range
can be obtained by clicking the "Normal" gadget. Once you have set the values
you require click on @{"Prefs" LINK "Prefs"} and save the prefs, this will store the 
percentages. The value of these percentages can be manually entered in the
@{"Prefs" LINK "Prefs"} window.

  The window can be sized by draging the size gadget on the bottom right of
the window. The window cannot be sized smaller that the default size (because
all the gadgets fall off the end) but it can be as large as your screen.
  To save the position and size of your window, first size and move it to the
required place and then click on @{"Prefs" LINK "Prefs"} and save the prefs.

 The Remind_GUI program is only used for changing the Remind data. When you
have applied all your changes then Remind_GUI can be Quit and removed from
memory. The controlling process Remind will restart Remind_GUI when it is
next required.
 If you just Finish Remind_GUI then it stays memory resident. Next time the
controlling program Remind requires Remind_GUI it does not have to reload
all the information again.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Add" "Adding a new message"
@TOC "MAIN"
                           Adding a new message

 Clicked on the 'Add' button, or selecting Add from the menu, or typing 'a' 
or 'ramiga-a' will open up the Add window for adding a new message.

 How to add a message.

1. Using the string gadget labelled 'Text' insert the message which you wish
   to be displayed.

2. Select the type of message you require.

  Once        - The message will after expiring move into the Previous 
                (top list) and will stay there until it become as old as 
                the value set in the @{"Preference" LINK "Prefs"} History size field, and 
                then it is removed.

  Persistant  - The message will be created at the day specified, but when 
                that date expires it will stay in the Today list until it 
                is 'Deleted'. @{"Finishing a persistant message." LINK "Persistant"}

  Weekly      - Once the message expires it is reissued a week later

  Monthly     - Once the message expires it is reissued 1 month later

  Annually    - Once the message expires it is reissued 1 year later

  Birthday    - This message behaves the same as annually and in effect is
                exactly the same as an Annual message. Selecting Birthday
                enters in the Prenote box the value set in the @{"preferences" LINK "Prefs"}
                for pre-note added days. On selecting birthday type you will
                be moved to enter the age at next birthday. When the birthday
		message appears you will be reminded of the persons age. This
		value is automatically updated every year, so you wont forget
		a major birthday!
		Note that the birthday message type can also be used for
		anniversaries, the messages will appear with a birthday type
		but the function is the same.

  Relative    - This message occurs on a set DAY in the month. Selecting this
                type swaps the input method to the Relative selectors.
                See step 3 for selecting the Relative day.
                This day occurs monthly on the same day of the week.
                So if you are say paid on the 1st Tuesday of every month then
                this is the type of message to use.

  Annual Relative 
              - This message is similar to Relative messages but instead of
		occurring every month they are relative to every year. So
		for example you can set a message for the 4th Thursday in
		November for "Thanks Giving."

  User Period
              - The period this message repeats is user definable. When this
				message type is selected the 'User Period' gadget will be
				enabled. Enter in this gadget the period this note should
				repeat for. E.g. 14 for every two weeks.

3. For non-Relative messages select the date you wish the message to occur
   on.
   Use the sliders to select the day/month,
   or press

      d - To increase day by one (note if you are on 30th June and you press 
          'd' you will go to 1st July etc.)

      D - To decrease the day by one.

      m - To increase the month by one.
 
      M - To decrease the month by one.

  Selecting the 'Today' button will reset the date to today.

  Selecting one of the 'Plus' button will add a set amount to the current 
date, e.g. Selecting '1 Month' to 15th June will result in the 15th July
being displayed at the bottom left of the window.

  
  For Relative types of message the "Week Number" slider is used to select
the week of the month the message will occur on, e.g. 1st week, 2nd week,...
Not every month has the same amount of weeks in it, so a "Last" box is added.
Clicking on the last box will find the last day in every month.
  The Week day slider selects the day of the week for the message to occur
on, e.g. Sunday, Monday, ...



4. All messages can have what is called a "Prenote" added to them.
   This is done by entering a value in the "Pre-note days" box.
   This value indicates how many days before the message is due another
   message should be issued to act as a reminder.

   For example, if a message is set up as follows:

       Text : Go on holiday
       Date : 25th July 1994
       Type : Once

  Then the pre-note days box may have the value 7 entered in it, then on the
  18th July 1994 a message "On 25th July: Go on holiday" will appear
  reminding you that the holiday is approaching and you should have obtained
  your passports by that time for example.

5. Each message can have with it an associated time. Click in the "Time" box
   will enable the hour and minute gadgets. Enter the time which the message
   should occur, the time is either entered in 24hour format or AM/PM format,
   see @{"Preferences" LINK "Prefs"} for details.
   If AM/PM format is being used then the time has to be entered and the
   cycle gadget selected as AM or PM.

   When this time is reached Remind activates a simple window displaying the
   time and the message.
 
6. A message can have associated with it a command to execute. Click on the
   execute command box to enable the command gadget, and enter the command
   you wish to execute for this message. See @{"Command Execution" LINK "Command"}.
  
7. Select either "Accept" or "Cancel" to accept or reject the message.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Command" "Command execution"
@TOC "MAIN"

                               Command Execution

  Any message can have associated with it a command string.
  This string is added to the message when you @{"create" LINK "Add"} or @{"amend" LINK "Amend"} and message.

  This feature can only accept simple one line commands, exactly the same
  as selecting "Execute Command" from the Workbench menu.

  The command is executed with the following.

      run <NIL: >NIL: <command>

  where <command> is the command you entered.

  The command is executed in one of two places.

  1. If the message has a time associated with it, the command will be
     executed at the same time the message window appears on the screen.
 
  2. If the message has no time associated with it, the command will be 
     executed the first time Remind is used on the date of the message.

  When a command is executed a window may or may not appear with the message
  depending if the "Window" flag was set next to the execute flag. This
  allows commands to be executed at a set time but with no interaction with
  Remind required.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Delete" "Delete a message"
@TOC "MAIN"
                                    Delete

  Any message can be selected by simply clicking on the message. If you wish
to delete the message simply click on 'Delete' or type 'd' or select 
'Delete' from the menu. The message is then deleted.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Amend" "Amend a message"
@TOC "MAIN"
                                    Amend


  Any message can be selected by simply clicking on the message. If you wish
to amend the message simple click on 'Amend' or type 'm' or select "Amend"
from the menu. A message can also be amended by double clicking on the actual
message. 

The amend window will appear which has the same functionality as the Add
window. Edit the message and date etc. and accept the message to replace it.
Clicking @{"'Cancel'" LINK "Main window"} or 'Close window' will ignore all your changes and close
the Amend window.

  In previous versions of Remind once a message of type "Persistant" has been
dealt with the user would either delete it, or amend its type to be Once.
This was a bit inconvenient as you lose the record of the message or amending
has to occur. See @{"Finishing a persistant message." LINK "Persistant"}

@ENDNODE 

@NODE "Persistant" "Finishing a persistant message"
@TOC "MAIN"

			Clearing a persistant message

  When you no longer require a persistant message to nag you everyday, it
can be changed by holding down shift and double clicking on the message. 
This moves the message to the "previous" window and it will act as a once 
type message which has expired.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Prefs" "Setting the preferences"
@TOC "MAIN"
                                Preferences

  The preferences give you more control on how the program behaves.

  Clicking on the 'Prefs' gadget will open the preference window.


Freeze remind until clock set:

  As described @{"earlier" LINK "No clock"}, when Remind starts if the
'Freeze remind until clock set' flag is set (i.e. a tick is present in the
little box) then when remind starts up it will waiting until you tell it to
continue. This allows you to set the system clock before the program
initialises.

Show messages for today:

  As described @{"earlier" LINK "Today messages"}, when Remind starts if this flag is set and there are
any messages for today then a small window will appear at startup displaying
the message.

24hour clock:

  The type of clock format for the program can be selected to be either
24 hour format, (00:00 -> 23:59) or AM/PM format (12:00AM -> 11:59PM).
If this flag has a tick in it then all clocks act on a 24hour basis.
  Changing this flag will not alter currently displayed time formats on the
screen, however any further time functions will adopt the new format and
next time the program is run all time formats will change.

View printout long format:

  In the @{"view" LINK "view"} section you can select 'print' when a list is
displayed. This printout can be in two formats.
  1. A direct copy of the screen listing, i.e. not long format.
  2. As a calendar view (long format) with every day shown.

Print File Name:

  If this option is selected then the output of Print in the @{"view" LINK "view"}
  section is sent to a file instead of the printer port. The file name can
  be specified.

Within period (days):

  The amount of days which are displayed separately in the Third list window
is determined by the value set in the Within Period field.
  For example if today is 7th June and the within period is set to 7 then 
the third list contains all messages for the,
  8th, 9th, 10th, 11th, 12th, 13th and 14th of June.

 
Length of history (days):

  This field determines how long expired messages are kept in the
Previous list, a value of 0 means all messages are kept in the history
buffer.


Timer for startup (secs):

  This sets the amount of seconds the @{"Startup window" LINK "Startup"} is displayed at the 
beginning. Setting this value to 0 turns off the startup window.


Pre-note added (days):

  This sets how many days before a 'Birthday' type message the Pre-note is 
set to. See the Add section for more detail.


On startup:

  The behaviour of the main window can be determined by selecting one of the
three:
    Always,
    Never,
    Once.

  Always - indicates that after the Startup window has closed the main window
           will be opened.

  Never  - indicates that the main window will never be opened and so the
           only method for opening it would be via the controlling process.

  Once   - The first time the program is used each day will result in the
           window being opened.


Initial Window:

  The position of the @{"Startup" LINK "Startup"} / @{"Waiting" LINK "No clock"} window can be set using the
'Initial Window' button. This opens up a small window which can be dragged to
the required opening position. Click on the close gadget to select the 
position.


Data file name:

  The path and name of the data file can be set here. So if you are unhappy 
that the program writes to your s: directory you could change it to something
more to your liking!


Remind window size:

  Please note, when the preferences are saved the current position and size
of the main window is saved with them.

List percentage size:
  When the preferences are saved the current percentage values for each
of the lists is saved with them.

Once the preferences have been set click on Save to write and use them, or
click on Cancel (or close the window) to ignore anything you have done.

Percentages:

 The percentage gadgets allow you to enter the exact percentages of the
four windows in the main screen. Note that these must add up to 100%.
If they do not then you will be unable to save the percentages.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Quit" "Does anyone read the window title?"
@TOC "MAIN"
                                   Quit

  This button completely shuts Remind down, removing it from memory.


@ENDNODE
@NODE "View" "Displaying a View"
@TOC "MAIN"
                                   View

  Due to popular demand a viewing feature has been added. This allows you
to see all events which will occur in the coming future. A list is produced
showing the events in order of which they occur.

  The time period for the view is completely defineably, and after clicking
on the View gadget you will be presented with a form to complete representing
the period you wish the view to be for.

  Simple select the start and finish dates or select the start date and
select a period to show, e.g. 1 week, 2 weeks, 3 months, 1 year.

  Select 'Done' and the events will be shown.

  Prenotes are ignored and persistant notes are shown only once.

  Once the list has been generated you can either select:

    'Quit' to finish the viewing.

    'Print' to print the list using the set @{"preferences" LINK "prefs}

    'Change' to re-select the from/to dates.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Finish" "Im bored of writing these"
@TOC "MAIN"
                              Finished / Hide

  This saves the database to disk and closes down the window. The program 
remains in memory and can be activated from the controlling process.




@ENDNODE

@NODE "Tools" "Tooltypes"
@TOC "MAIN"
                                 TOOLTYPES


Remind currently only knows of 2 tooltypes.

HOTKEY - Defining the hotkey to use

         e.g.   HOTKEY=shift f8

CX_PRIORITY - The priority level in the commodities



NOTE: The DONOTWAIT tooltype has to be included so Workbench will not wait
for a return when remind is run from WBStartup draw.
  - If anyone could tell me how to remove this then it would be appreciated.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Bugs" "Anyone know any good jokes. Email them to me."
@TOC "MAIN"
                               Known bugs :)

  PLEASE NOTE.

    When reporting bugs to me (please do) a little information makes my life
easier. Things like..

>  When I enter a note of type "blurr" and then click accept and then quit
>  and when the requester appears I select "save" my computer blows up.

Indicating a step by step approach to how the bug occurrs.

Also information (especially if it is a display problem) such as

Screen mode:  e.g. PAL/NTSC ?  Hi-res laced, Low-res, Super hi-res ?
Screen size:  Default width/height or e.g, width=1500 ?
Default font: topaz 9, Gothic 54, etc?
Default screen font: ....


Help me to help you.

---------

 Known Bugs:

 To generate a view of > 2 years, the age of the birthday messages
does not increase.

@ENDNODE

